Introduction

According to the latest WWF report, the average population size of terrestrial vertebrates has fallen by 68% In less than 50 years.1 However, recent studies have even suggested that the dynamics of biodiversity are not really declining on average. They postulate that species at risk are dragging down global indices,2 but that there are as many âwinnersâ as âlosersâ species in total.3 These last results have mainly been documented through the BioTIME database.4 In this report, we propose to re-evaluate this through the Living Planet Database. We also aim to investigate whether population dynamics are influenced by climate change.

Population changes

Methods

The database considered contains 1212 species of terrestrial vertebrates and 5529 population time series distributed worldwide. We only focused on time series beginning after 1980 in order to be consistent with the climate data we analyse in the following part.

Each population time series was fitted with a linear regression model to quantify the trend through:

\[\begin{eqnarray*} X(t) = \alpha_{0} + \alpha_{1}t + \epsilon(t) \end{eqnarray*}\]

Where \(X\) is the abundance estimate, \(t\) the time in years, with process error represented by \(\epsilon\) ~ \(N\)(0,\(\sigma\)Â²).

Results

The following map illustrates the distribution of the time series. Each point is colored according to its trend and sized according to the magnitude of its trend.

Among the 5529, 1920 are increasing, 1742 are decreasing and 1573 are showing constant trends (p>0.05).
